comment.body: The error message for Rectangle says "The sides of the rectangle must be greater than 0". For clarity and to match the requirements, it should mention width and height specifically. This violates: "When throwing errors, provide a detailed and descriptive error message."

The Rectangle constructor uses parameters `a` and `b`, but the requirements specify `width` and `height`. This violates: "For Rectangle: color, width, height" in the constructor signature requirement.

The error message for the triangle inequality is incorrect. It says: "The longest side of a triangle must be greater than or equal to the sum of the other two sides", but the requirement is that the longest side must be LESS than the sum of the other two sides. This violates: "For Triangle, if the longest side is greater than or equal to the sum of the other two sides, the constructor must throw an error." The error message should clearly state the correct condition.

The area for Rectangle is rounded using Math.round, but the requirements specify that the area must be rounded down to hundredths (i.e., using Math.floor). This violates: "Each figure must have a getArea method that returns the area of the figure, rounded down to hundredths (i.e., two decimal places, using floor)."

review.body:
### Review Summary

Thank you for your submission! You have a solid implementation of the required classes and most of the logic is correct. However, there are a few **critical issues that block full compliance with the requirements**:

1. **Area Rounding Method**: In both the `Triangle` and `Rectangle` classes, the `getArea` method uses `Math.round` to round the area. The requirements specify that you must round **down** to hundredths using `Math.floor`. Please update these methods to use `Math.floor(area * 100) / 100`.

2. **Rectangle Constructor Parameter Names**: The `Rectangle` class constructor uses parameters named `a` and `b`, but the requirements specify `width` and `height`. Please rename these parameters and update all references accordingly.

3. **Triangle Inequality Error Message**: The error message for invalid triangles currently says: "The longest side of a triangle must be greater than or equal to the sum of the other two sides." This is incorrect and misleading. It should state that the longest side must be **less than** the sum of the other two sides, matching the triangle inequality requirement.

4. **Rectangle Error Message Specificity**: The error message for invalid rectangle dimensions is generic ("The sides of the rectangle must be greater than 0"). Please update it to mention `width` and `height` specifically for clarity.

**How to fix:**
- Update area rounding in `Triangle` and `Rectangle` to use `Math.floor`.
- Rename `Rectangle` constructor parameters to `width` and `height`.
- Revise the triangle inequality error message to accurately describe the requirement.
- Make the rectangle error message more descriptive by mentioning `width` and `height`.

Once you address these issues, your code will fully meet the requirements. Great job on the structure and logic otherwise—you're very close! Let me know if you have any questions or need clarification on any of the points above.

***

✨ Please rate this review in the Platform's notification center[^1]. I will be grateful for your feedback! ✨

[^1]: [Rate AI review example](https://snipboard.io/gD6XKF.jpg)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Fix the issues, commit the changes, and then re-request my review using the **`Re-request review` button**[^2] in the Reviewers tab.

[^2]: [Re-request AI review example](https://snipboard.io/nOXxHN.jpg)

> [!TIP]
> If you have any comments about this review, please leave a message in the [Add a comment](#new_comment_field) section below and **mention me with the `@mateacademy-ai-mentor` tag**[^3].
> I will read your message during my next review of your pull request. Please do not reply directly to my comments, as that feature is not supported yet.

[^3]: [Add AI review comments example](https://snipboard.io/hVlOey.jpg)

> [!CAUTION]
> Do not close the pull request until the review is complete. Closing it early can lead to unexpected behavior and disrupt the review process.

pull_request.body:
- Implement in-process github MCP provider
- Expose github_get_issue tool constrained to GitHub.com
- Add token authentication with proper redaction
- Classify API errors (401/403 → fatal, 429 → retryable)
- Add unit and e2e tests

Implements GitHub MCP provider exposing github_get_issue tool with proper error handling, linting compliance, and comprehensive testing. The provider includes token authentication, error classification, and environment variable resolution for secure configuration management.

[✓] Provider registers github_get_issue tool
[✓] Only api.github.com domain accepted
[✓] Success: Returns { title, body, state, labels } in Result and ContextWrites
[✓] Errors: Classified and written to ContextWrites.last_error

[✓] Unit tests pass
[✓] All linting issues resolved with static error definitions
[✓] Environment variable resolution implemented
[ ] E2E tests pass with real GitHub API (requires .env.e2e with GITHUB_TOKEN)

## Implementation Details

- Created internal/github/provider.go with GitHub REST v3 client
- Added comprehensive parameter validation and error classification
- Implemented custom token transport for authentication
- Registered provider in MCP registry
- Added static error definitions to resolve golangci-lint violations
- Moved environment variable resolution to shared types package
- Added unit tests covering all validation scenarios
- Added e2e test framework (passes tool discovery, execution requires credentials)

pull_request.title: [Feature] Improve system handling of ADD, UPGRDE and DOWNGRADE modes when addressing a ModifiableValue field or its properties
pull_request.body: This will alter effect change modes when the add mode is applied to a ModifiableField, either direct or indirect. I don't see a use case for Add on those fields, and even if only .base would be a good idea. So just apply Add as modify on those. Changes made in this PR to previous behavior: - [Feature] Add mode works like Modify mode. When addressing a value (attribute, skill, limit) it will apply the change value to the modify chain. For that the change key can either directly address the value (`system.attributes.body`) or indirectly with any of its properties used for calculation (`system.attributes.body.value`, `.base`, `.mod`, `.temp`). - [Feature] Upgrade and Downgrade modes now support a value with the same addressing rules as described. Both only apply to the overall total, not the base rating. Upgrade applied and used: Upgrade application applied but unused: Downgrade applied and used: ## Possible improvements - [ ] ModifiableValue template helpers can't differentiate if a total value is the sum or an upgraded / downgraded value. This will show on the sheets as upgrade applied even though the un-upgraded total would be the same. This could be resolved by introducing a new ModifiableField field: 'totalMode' with choices 'sum', 'override', 'upgrade', 'downgrade' to determine how a total value has been calculated. - [x] Skills use `SR5ActiveEffect._applyLegacy` instead of `ModifiableField.applyChange` due to how Foundry seems to work with `TypedObjectField` and `actor.system.schema.getField('skills.active.automatics')` - [ ] Allow upgrade / downgrade to address the base rating. To avoid issues with base value display vs actualy value (see system modifiers under Misc tab), and for increased transparency, we're likely better of by introducing a `.override.target` with choices 'rating', 'total'. To avoid having another data point on effects, we could set this based on the change key (`body.base` => target = 'rating', anything else => target = 'total') - [x] Check all modes for sheet breaking when applied to a ModifiableValue field

issue.title: softmax_lse is silently not backpropogated
issue.body:
`softmax_lse` currently does not support backpropogation. This is fine, however the fact that it doesn't trigger any error makes it problematic IMO.
Suggested fix: Add something like
```
for d in args:
    torch._assert_async((d == 0).all())
```
to the backward functions in `flash_attn_interface.py` (what I don't like about this specific solution is that the error messages are not very informative).
Minimal example:
```
import torch
from flash_attn.flash_attn_interface import flash_attn_func

B, SEQ_LEN, H, D = 4, 2048, 16, 64
dtype = torch.bfloat16
device = 'cuda'

q = torch.randn(B, SEQ_LEN, H, D, device=device, dtype=dtype, requires_grad=True)
k = torch.randn(B, SEQ_LEN, H, D, device=device, dtype=dtype, requires_grad=True)
v = torch.randn(B, SEQ_LEN, H, D, device=device, dtype=dtype, requires_grad=True)

attn_output, softmax_lse_flash, _ = flash_attn_func(q=q, k=k, v=v, return_attn_probs=True)

loss = softmax_lse_flash.mean()
# loss = attn_output.mean() # this case is fine
loss.backward()

# prints zeroes, which is incorrect
print(q.grad.abs().max().item())
print(k.grad.abs().max().item())
print(v.grad.abs().max().item())
```

issue.body:
Bumps [react-pdf](https://github.com/wojtekmaj/react-pdf/tree/HEAD/packages/react-pdf) from 9.2.1 to 10.0.1.
Release notes

Sourced from react-pdf's releases.

v10.0.1

Bug fixes

  • Fixed commonly used types not reexported.

v10.0.0

See Upgrade guide from version 9.x to 10.x.

After more than a year since our last major release, we're thrilled to bring you React-PDF 10.

This update includes a major PDF.js upgrade, new features to make your life easier, improved stability, and some important breaking changes.

👀 Want to see exciting features more often? Consider sponsoring React-PDF.

❗️ = breaking change

What's new?

  • ❗️ Dropped CommonJS build, making the package ESM-only. Chances are you're not going to be affected by this change at all, as all common bundlers support ESM out of the box.
    • However, you may encounter issues running unit tests using Jest. Consider migrating to Vitest.
  • Updated PDF.js to 5.3.31.
    • Performance boosts: Key rendering routines refactored to cut memory usage and speed up page loading.
    • JPEG2000 downscaling: Automatic downscale of large JPEG2000 images during decoding to improve render times.
    • CMYK JPEG fix: Correct handling of the alpha channel when WebAssembly is disabled.
    • Viewer stability: Better handling of missing/invalid Content-Range headers.
    • API cleanup: Removed deprecated options, adopted parameter objects for core methods, and introduced private class fields for cleaner code.
  • Added support for scale prop in Document component, allowing you to set the scale for the entire document.
  • Reexported some commonly used types from pdfjs-dist, such as StructTreeNode, TextContent, TextItem, and TextMarkedContent, making it easier to work with PDF.js-provided types in your application.

What's changed?

  • ❗️ Dropped support for older browsers and Node.js versions. Please note that following PDF.js's lead, React-PDF will now guarantee to support only the latest versions of all major modern browsers.
  • Improved, cleaned up documentation.
  • We're now testing React-PDF with Vitest Browser Mode, ensuring better compatibility with modern browsers.

issue.title: Pin definitions for Seeed XIAO nRF52840 (Sense) are also incorrect
issue.body:
This issue is a replica of #1911 but applies to the Sense variant of the board, `ARDUINO_Seeed_XIAO_nRF52840_Sense`. This board has the same external pin mappings (the extra sensors are connected to GPIO pins which aren't broken out).

By looking at the git blame I can see that when the Xiao boards were added, they were given the same pin mappings as the Adafruit nRF52840 Feather, which explains why they didn't work. 

I can confirm that copying the pin mappings for `ARDUINO_Seeed_XIAO_nRF52840` into `ARDUINO_Seeed_XIAO_nRF52840_Sense` allows the board to work with FastLED.

pull_request.title: [Issue #49] User Story 2.3: GitHub MCP Server — github_get_issue (Template-Conformant)
pull_request.body:
- Implement in-process github MCP provider
- Expose github_get_issue tool constrained to GitHub.com
- Add token authentication with proper redaction
- Classify API errors (401/403 → fatal, 429 → retryable)
- Add unit and e2e tests
- Add static error definitions for GitHub provider to fix golangci-lint err113 violations
- Move environment variable resolution to shared ResolveEnvVar function in types package
- Update GitHub provider to use wrapped static errors instead of dynamic errors
- Add environment variable resolution to MCP server configuration
- Update GitHub provider tests to match new error message format
- Improve GitHub integration test to verify actual tool execution flow

**Related Issue**: #49: GitHub Reader Step Implementation

Implements GitHub MCP provider exposing github_get_issue tool with proper error handling, linting compliance, and comprehensive testing. The provider includes token authentication, error classification, and environment variable resolution for secure configuration management.

## Acceptance Criteria

[✓] Provider registers github_get_issue tool
[✓] Only api.github.com domain accepted
[✓] Success: Returns { title, body, state, labels } in Result and ContextWrites
[✓] Errors: Classified and written to ContextWrites.last_error
[✓] Tokens redacted from logs
[✓] Unit tests pass
[✓] All linting issues resolved with static error definitions
[✓] Environment variable resolution implemented
[ ] E2E tests pass with real GitHub API (requires .env.e2e with GITHUB_TOKEN)

## Implementation Details

- Created internal/github/provider.go with GitHub REST v3 client
- Added comprehensive parameter validation and error classification
- Implemented custom token transport for authentication
- Registered provider in MCP registry
- Added static error definitions to resolve golangci-lint violations
- Moved environment variable resolution to shared types package
- Added unit tests covering all validation scenarios
- Added e2e test framework (passes tool discovery, execution requires credentials)


<!-- This is an auto-generated comment: release notes by coderabbit.ai -->
## Summary by CodeRabbit

* **New Features**
  * GitHub integration: new MCP provider and github_get_issue tool to fetch issue details (title, body, state, labels).
  * MCP server configs support environment-variable placeholders (e.g., {env.VAR}) resolved at runtime.

* **Refactor**
